{
  "texts": [
    "Now let Z = {x ∈ A | x ∈ F }.First, we claim that Z is a proper filter in A, so Z ∈ A g. Suppose x ∈ Z, so x ∈ F, and x ≤ A y.",
    "Since x and y are the sets of proper filters in A containing x and y, respectively, x ≤ A y implies that any proper filter that contains x also contains y, so x ⊆ y and hence x ≤ (Ag) b y.",
    "Then since x ∈ F and F is a filter in (A g) b, we have y ∈ F and hence y ∈ Z.",
    "Thus, Z is an upset in A.",
    "Next, if x, y ∈ Z, then x, y ∈ F, so x ∩ y ∈ F because F is a filter in (A g) b, so x ∧ y ∈ F by the fact that x ∩ y = x ∧ y (recall the proof of Theorem 5.31), so x ∧ y ∈ Z."
  ]
}